result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant appeared in custody in person from Jackson County Jail with his counsel SPD Carly Sebion.  Gerald Fox appears for the State.  DA Fox states there was no response from the victim in 14CF79 and the firearm was recovered.  There was also no response from the victim in 14CF172.  He will plead to counts 1, 2, and 3 in 14CF172.  Count 4 and all other remaininig cases will be dismissed and read-in.   In 14CF172 defendant pleads no contest to counts 1, 2, and 3.  Judge reviews plea questionnaire/waiver of rights/elements with defendant.  He verifies repeater status.  Defense stipulates that factual a basis exists.  Court finds the defendant understands the proceedings and freely, voluntarily, intelligently wavies his rights and enters his pleas.  Finding of guilty to counts 1, 2, and 3 in 14CF172 with count 4 dismissed and read-in.  Also dismissed and read-in are 14CF79, 14CF180, 14CF116, and 14TR3676.  Sentenced withheld and placed on probation for 3 years concurrent on all 3 counts.  Court granted 156 days sentence credit on count 3 only.  Conditions of probation are:    The defendant shall comply with any treatment, evaluations and/or programming as deemed appropriate by the COMPAS assessment and the probation agent.  Defendant must sign any releases agent deems necessary to verify defendant's compliance with probation conditions.  Must participate in and successfully complete DV Court if agent deems appropriate.  Must seek and maintain full-time employment when your agent feels it will work with your counseling schedule and the employment must be satisfactory to your probation.  You must not leave or change employment without prior approval of your probation agent.  Not to enter into any bars, taverns, liquor stores, liquor department of grocery stores, the bar areas of restaurants. Defendant may not possess or consume any alcohol, nor be anywhere alcohol is available for consumption on the premises where the defendant is located except for employment purposes only.  Contact with the victim in 14CF172 will be at your agent's discretion.  Must be fitted with a SCRAM unit at first report to agent.  May not be removed until agent deems appropriate.  Must comply with all rules of SCRAM usage and all rules of probation and any other recommendations of your agent.  Must pay the costs of the action and costs of supervision.

Defendant shall not consume any alcohol unless a physician states in writing that the defendant is alcohol dependent and complete withdrawal could endanger the defendant's health or life. In this case a doctor's excuse must be submitted to the Jackson County Clerk of Court or the Jackson County Jail within 48 hours of the bond being signed. Not to enter into any bars, taverns, liquor stores, liquor department of grocery stores, bar areas of restaurants, or where available for consumption on the premises where the defendant is located.  As a condition of your release, you must be available 24 hours per day, 7 days a week to submit to testing for alcohol when requested by a law enforcement officer or your probation agent. The defendant may submit to an alcohol test at the Jackson County Sheriff's Office or submit to a PBT by a law enforcement officer. Upon request, the defendant shall appear for and submit to testing within two (2) hours of the official's request.  Not to possess or consume any controlled substances.   Not to possess any drug paraphernalia.  Not to possess any prescription medications of any kind unless those have been prescribed to the defendant by a physician, and in that case, the defendant shall take such medications only as prescribed.  Defendant shall not alter the form of any prescription prior to, or in conjunction with, ingestion. Not to possess any firearms.
